~ monk_cavern
Monk: Most men never leave the cave. They grow fond of the shadows... and call them truth.

Monk: Yet the philosopher wrote of one prisoner who ascended slowly toward the light. Not at the beginning of his teachings, where ignorance still reigns...nor near the end, where wisdom already stands unveiled.

Monk: The revelation lies deeper within the work — after the sixth step of understanding, just before the eighth.

Monk: There, the prisoner first sees the world for what it truly is.

Monk: Find the passage. Speak its title.
Monk: Only then will the stone door open.
=> END

~ descartes
Descartes: I learned long ago that the senses deceive us more often than they guide us.

Descartes: Thus, I resolved to doubt everything — every belief, every certainty, every shadow mistaken for truth.

Descartes: But doubt itself revealed something undeniable: if I question, then I must think; and if I think, then I must exist.

Descartes: From that single certainty, I began constructing knowledge anew, step by step, method by method.

Descartes: Many remember the conclusion, yet forget where the journey truly begins: not with answers, but with reason ordered carefully upon itself.

Descartes: If you seek the path forward, do as I once did.
Descartes: Follow the discourse... and look to the second part, where method first takes form.
=> END

~ adollshouse
Doll: They placed me neatly upon the shelf long before I understood I was living inside a performance.

Doll: A perfect wife, a delicate voice, a smiling little ornament for the house... that was all Nora was ever meant to be.

Doll: She danced when told to dance. Laughed when told to laugh. Even her secrets existed only to protect the comfort of others.

Doll: But a doll that learns it has strings begins to notice the hands pulling them.

Doll: In the end, she chose something unforgivable: herself.

Doll: Doors closed behind her that night — loudly enough for the whole world to hear.

Doll: So if you seek escape, perhaps the answer lies not in philosophers or republics... but in the woman who walked away from her little doll’s house.

Doll: Nora always knew how to leave a room.
